{[%evp 0,31,23,32,22,-8,4,4,7,3,3,5,0,7,19,-32,-35,2,21,-33,-5,-5,2,24,26,28,
29,29,30,30,41,18,40,77]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Bb4
{Black is aiming to play the Ragozin, although the king's knight is still on
g1. This yields White an additional and important possibility of ..Nge2 at
once or after Bf1-d3.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 {The pin is viable.} ({Less offers} 7.
Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 Qd6 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 Bf5 {Black is close to equality.})
7... g5 {The most common and consistent. Black is aiming to occupy the key
e4-spot and increase the pressure on the Nc3.} ({After} 7... O-O 8. Bd3 {
, Black has an inferior version of the Carlsbad, as the Bb4 is misplaced. For
instance,} c5 9. Nge2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 (10. exd4 $5 {also might suffice for a
small advantage.}) 10... Nc6 11. O-O Nxd4 12. exd4 Be7 13. Re1 $14 {In this
position with a symmetric pawn structure, White has a stable advantage due to
his more active pieces. Andreikin,D - Hong,A Chess.com INT 2022}) (7... c5 {
can be well met by} 8. Bb5+ $1 Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. Nge2 $14 {The d5-pawn
felt very weak in Zhou,J - Lu, S Tianjin 2011}) 8. Bg3 Ne4 ({In the event of} 
8... h5 9. Qb3 Bxc3+ {, I present the following new idea:} 10. bxc3 $146 ({
After} 10. Qxc3 Nc6 11. Bb5 Bd7 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. f3 h4 {, Black had decent
counterplay due to his superior development in Bykov,O -Paravyan,D Sochi 2020})
10... h4 ({After} 10... Ne4 11. f3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 Qd6 13. g4 $36 {, both kings
are in the centre, but White's is much safer due to his superior pawn
structure.}) 11. Be5 Nbd7 12. Nf3 {White is getting ready for the exchange on
e5.} g4 13. Nd2 c6 14. Bf4 $14 {The strong unopposed dark-squared bishop
offers White the better chances.}) 9. a3 {This move has only been seen in a
couple of games so far, but I find it very logical: it forces Black to concede
his very important bishop and get rid of the pin.} ({The more common} 9. Nge2
h5 10. h4 {leads to major complications, and Black seems to have decent
counterplay.}) 9... Bxc3+ ({The main tactical point of White's last move is} 
9... Nxc3 10. Qb3 $1 {White regains the piece under favourable circumstances.}
Bxa3 ({After} 10... Ne4+ 11. axb4 Nxg3 12. hxg3 $16 {, White is much better
due to his control of the h-file and his stable space advantage.}) 11. bxc3 Be7
12. Nf3 c6 {This position occurred in Hammer,J - Lodici,L Antalya 2017 Here my
natural improvement over White's play is} 13. Bd3 $146 Nd7 14. c4 Nb6 15. c5
Nd7 16. h4 $36 {Black's position is very cramped, and his king is in permanent
danger.}) 10. bxc3 h5 (10... c5 {was played in Kapnisis,S - Ketzetzis,G Kavala
2008 Here I like} 11. dxc5 $1 $146 {White opens the position and isolates the
d5-pawn, although at the cost of creating some weaknesses of his own.} Nc6 ({
Also after} 11... Qa5 12. Ne2 Be6 13. Be5 Rg8 14. Nc1 $1 Qxc5 15. Bd4 {, White
has a stable initiative due to his bishop pair and safer king.}) 12. Bd3 Qa5
13. Ne2 $14 {Black will regain the pawn, but he is way overextended.}) 11. f3 {
Not only liberating the bishop but also preparing the standard expansion with
e3-e4.} Nxg3 ({I also examined} 11... h4 12. Be5 f6 13. fxe4 fxe5 14. Nf3 $36 {
The knight will enter the centre with great effect.}) 12. hxg3 Qd6 ({After} 
12... Nc6 13. Kf2 h4 14. gxh4 gxh4 15. Ne2 {, White's king is safe. After the
knight reaches f4, Black will suffer from his damaged pawn structure.}) 13. g4
$1 {The most energetic. White fixes f5 for his future outpost.} h4 14. Bd3 Nc6
15. Nh3 Qg3+ 16. Kf1 {Black doesn't have any attack, while his structural
drawbacks are obvious. Yu,Y-Dubov,D chess24.com INT 2020} *

