{[%evp 0,35,23,22,35,4,7,7,18,0,5,10,13,22,9,42,57,39,39,-18,42,-3,47,22,31,24,
24,24,34,34,59,62,59,58,41,19,34,23]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5
5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Qb6 {This straightforward attempt to unpin the f6-knight is
dubious because Black lacks development.} 7. Qc2 {I see nothing wrong with
this traditional Carlsbad move.} ({Another natural continuation that was
successfully tested in practice is} 7. Qd2 $5 Ne4 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. a3) 7... Ne4
{Only this aggressive move has a logical connection with 6...Qb6.} ({After} 
7... Na6 8. Bxa6 Qxa6 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nge2 Be6 11. O-O {, White has the
better pawn structure, while Black lacks development. Solmundarson,
M-Sigurjonsson,J Reykjavik 1982}) ({Pointless is} 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. Nge2
{White has played all the regular Carlsbad moves, while the Qb6 is clearly
misplaced.}) 8. Bf4 ({The materialistic} 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Qxe4+ Be6 {leaves
White with some concrete problems in view of the threats on the a5-e1 diagonal.
} 10. O-O-O Qa5 11. Nf3 Qxa2 {leads to double-edged play.}) ({However,} 8. Bh4
$5 Bf5 9. Bd3 Na6 10. a3 {is also worth attention.}) 8... Bf5 ({In the event of
} 8... Na6 9. Bxa6 Qxa6 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qxe4+ Be6 {I now prefer} 12. f3 $1
Be7 13. Ne2 O-O 14. Kf2 $16 {White has a strong extra pawn and the king is
safe on f2. Kollberg,L-Moehring,G Colditz 1967}) (8... Bd6 {was also tried by
strong players.} 9. Bxd6 Nxd6 10. Bd3 {This is played on time - White
shouldn't let Black play ...Bf5 so easily.} g6 {The most consistent. This
position occured in Lautier,J - Flear,G Dortmund 1989. Here I present the
following promising idea:} ({In case of} 10... Nd7 11. Nge2 Nf6 {Magat,J -
Repkova,E Slovakia 2016 , I like} 12. Nf4 $146 O-O 13. O-O-O Be6 14. f3 {
Black suffers due to his passive e6-bishop and White has good attacking
prospects.}) 11. h4 $1 $146 {this might make Black regret ...g7-g6.} h5 {
This move makes Black's setup more unstable.} ({After} 11... Bf5 12. Bxf5 Nxf5
13. h5 $36 {White's attack is very strong.}) 12. Nf3 Bf5 13. Bxf5 Nxf5 {
In this case the Nf5 is misplaced, as it can be attacked by g2-g4 or e3-e4.}
14. O-O-O Nd7 15. Rhe1 $36 {Black struggles to secure his king.}) 9. Bd3 Na6
10. a3 {The Na6 is placed awkwardly now.} ({Of course, not} 10. Nxe4 $2 Nb4 11.
Qe2 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Bxe4 $19) 10... Qa5 11. Ra2 $1 {A decent prophylactic move.
Now the a3-pawn is unpinned, so Black's tactical abilities (such as Nb4 or Bb4)
are heavily limited. Also, White threatens to play 12.b4 next.} ({Less offers} 
11. Rc1 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 13. Rxc3 Bxd3 14. Rxd3 Kd7 {, and the position is
too simplistic.}) 11... Nxc3 ({The ''neutral''} 11... Be7 $6 {runs into} 12. b4
$1 Qd8 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bxa6 bxa6 15. Qxc6+ $16 {Black doesn't have
compensation for the pawn.}) 12. bxc3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc7 {Black hardly has
anything better than getting the knight into play.} 14. a4 $1 Qa6 {The queen
trade might favour Black, but in this case the knight will be stuck on a6
again.} ({In case of} 14... Be7 15. Rb2 $1 {, Black has no good way to defend
the pawn. In particular, after} O-O-O 16. Nf3 $16 {, Black's king is under a
strong attack.}) 15. Qxa6 Nxa6 16. Nf3 {This time it makes sense to leave e2
for the king.} f6 17. Ke2 b6 18. Rb1 $14 {White has the better chances due to
his more active pieces and good prospects in the centre. Spiegel,W - Rivas
Maceda,J ICCF email 2017} *

