{[%evp 0,29,22,22,35,7,7,18,18,5,7,14,22,12,28,28,31,24,32,32,19,22,26,29,29,
20,25,21,37,21,32,3]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3
Be6 {A relatively rare move. The idea is similar to 6...h6 7.Bh4 Be6, and in
some cases it can transpose into one of the positions from that Chapter, but
there is a difference. First of all, White isn't obliged to retreat his bishop
on g3 in response to ...h7-h6 and g7-g5.} 7. Bd3 Nbd7 (7... h6 8. Bh4 Nbd7 {
will be a direct transposition to the above-mentioned Chapter.}) 8. f3 {
The same approach as after 6...h6 & Be6 - White secures a retreat for his
bishop and prepares e3-e4.} Be7 (8... h6 9. Bh4 {transposes to 6...h6 7.Bh7 Be6
}) ({In the event of} 8... Bd6 9. Nge2 Qe7 (9... h6 10. Bh4 {is covered via 6..
.h6 & Be6 Chapter}) 10. O-O O-O-O {I prefer} 11. a4 $5 h6 12. Bf4 Bxf4 13. Nxf4
$14 {White has the better attacking prospects because b2-b4 will follow soon.})
9. Nge2 h6 10. Bh4 Nb6 ({In case of} 10... O-O 11. O-O {White has all the
chances to play e3-e4 at a proper moment. For instance,} Re8 12. Bf2 {
Protecting d4 and covering e3 in advance.} (12. Nf4 $5 {is also an attractive
option.}) 12... Nf8 13. h3 {The last preparations - now g4 is covered, so
Black's counter-attacking ideas are limited.} Rc8 14. e4 $14 {Black was
cramped in Hambleton,A - Avramidou,A Chess.com INT 2021}) 11. O-O O-O 12. Qc2 {
White has played all his regular moves while the placement of the e6-bishop
and the b6-knight isn't optimal.} Rc8 13. Rad1 c5 {This was Raupp,T - Mueller,
M Baden 2018 In my opinion, it makes sense to avoid the nasty opposition on
the c-file with} 14. Qb1 $146 a6 15. Kh1 $14 {White's position is better
because of his more active pieces. Now it is possible to switch to play
against the isolated pawn with dxc5 or start aggressive actions on the
kingside with ..g2-g4.} *

