{[%evp 0,33,22,22,26,7,18,24,18,14,14,14,22,22,25,1,22,-4,28,26,27,16,21,16,47,
17,56,57,63,61,58,38,55,64,73,79]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5.
Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 h6 8. Bh4 b6 {By making this move, Black shows his
intention to play with ''hanging pawns'', since ...c7-c5 should follow sooner
or later. This setup was popular decades ago - in particular, it was tested in
a few games from the candidates match Kasparov - Beliavsky.} 9. Nf3 {This was
a favourite choice of Garry's, and I trust him, although 9.Nge2!? also yields
White good results by statistics.} Bb7 ({The other way of development is} 9...
Be6 10. O-O c5 {, but as practice proves, after} 11. Ne5 {, the Be6 is often
vulnerable to f2-f4-f5. For instance,} Nfd7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. f4 Nxe5 14. dxe5
$40 {Black struggles to withstand the pawn storm on the kingside.
Dzindzichashvili,R - Rea, A New York 1996}) ({It hardly makes much sense to
start with} 9... c5 10. O-O Nc6 (10... Bb7 {is a transposition to the mainline.
}) 11. Rc1 $1 {Now the opposition of White's rook and Black's knight on the
c-file is rather uncomfortable for Black.} Bb7 ({After} 11... Be6 12. Bb5 Rc8
13. Qa4 $16 {, Black got under strong pressure on the light squares in a
classical game Vidmar,M-Tartakower,S Semmering 1926}) ({Hardly better is} 11...
c4 12. Bb1 Bb7 13. Ne5 {, with f2-f4 to follow. White's attack will outweigh
Black's expansion on the queenside.}) 12. Bb1 Rc8 13. dxc5 bxc5 {Natural play
by both sides led to this position in Perez Suarez, J-Fernandez Baniago,F
Asturias 2001. Here my new idea is} 14. Bxf6 $146 Bxf6 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Nxd5
Bxb2 17. Rxc5 $14 {Black doesn't have sufficient play for the pawn.}) 10. O-O
c5 ({The attempt to deviate from challenging White's pawn centre with} 10...
Nbd7 11. Qc2 Re8 {is hardly a sensible idea:} (11... c5 {leads to
transposition.}) 12. Rad1 Rc8 (12... a6) 13. Bf5 {The pressure of White's
bishops feel very annoying, so Black has nothing better than playing} c5 {
anyways, but now it is a worse version:} 14. Ne5 cxd4 15. exd4 $16 {Despite
the symmetric pawn structure, Black's position was very cramped in Injac,T -
Nurgali,N Moscow 2019.}) 11. Qc2 {I like this flexible continuation: After
Rad1, White should reach an optimal setup.} (11. Ne5 $5 {, as was played by
Kasparov almost 40 years ago, still seems promising for White:} Nbd7 12. Bf5
Nxe5 13. dxe5 Ne8 14. Bg3 {Black's king feels more exposed after h7-h6 is
played. Kasparov,G - Beliavsky,A Moscow 1983 Candidates}) 11... Nbd7 (11... Nc6
12. a3 c4 ({The alternatives are:} 12... cxd4 13. exd4 Nh5 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15.
Qd2 Nf6 16. Qf4 $14 {The symmetric pawn structure didn't offer Black easy play
because of the poor b7-bishop. Bitsch,T - Hirsch,G Baden 2017}) (12... a6 13.
dxc5 bxc5 {took place in Ivanchuk,V - Karpov,A Moscow 2008 In my opinion,
White should have continued:} 14. Rad1 $1 $146 d4 15. Na4 Nd7 16. Bg3 $36 {
White's pieces are perfectly mobilized for attacking the opponent's hanging
pawns.}) 13. Bf5 a6 14. Rad1 b5 15. Ne5 $36 {Black managed to make some
progress on the queenside, but White's initiative in the centre prevails.
Gupta,A - Sochacki,C Cappelle la Grande 2016}) 12. Bf5 {I find this move the
most precise: White moves his bishop in view of the coming...c5-c4. Also, the
Bf5 generally feels quite annoying for Black, as it puts pressure on the
d7-knight.} Re8 ({After} 12... c4 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 {, Fileru,M -
Celea,A Calimanesti 2018, White should have kept the attacking potential with}
15. Bg3 $1 $146 Nc5 16. Rad1 $36) ({Black can force the bishop's trade with} 
12... Nh5 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 {, but then the h5-knight is clearly misplaced. For
instance,} 14. Rfd1 Nhf6 15. Bxd7 $1 {A well-timed exchange that weakens c5.}
Qxd7 16. dxc5 bxc5 17. Na4 c4 18. Nc3 $14 {Black was doomed to passive defence
with a poor b7-bishop and a weak d5-pawn in Dussol,P - Heddache,R Chanac 1989})
({The ''academic''} 12... a6 {is well met by} 13. dxc5 $1 bxc5 14. Rfd1 {
, with massive pressure on the hanging pawns. Play might continue:} Qc7 15. Na4
Rfd8 16. Rac1 {Black struggles to defend c5 now.} Bc6 17. Bxd7 Bxd7 18. Nxc5
$16 {Peredy,F - Letay,G Hungary 2001}) 13. Rad1 c4 {An ambitious but very
risky approach - by releasing the tension in the centre, Black makes it much
easier for White to develop the attack.} ({After} 13... a6 14. Ne5 cxd4 15.
exd4 Nf8 16. Qb3 {, White had a powerful initiative due to his more active
pieces in Akopian,V - Vladimirov,Y Kolkata 2000}) 14. Ne5 {As usual, the
attack is based on this strong centralized knight.} a6 15. a4 {White has time
to prevent the nasty ...b6-b5.} Nf8 16. b3 g6 17. Bh3 $36 {Black's play on the
queenside came to an end, while the activity of all white pieces is getting
threatening. Cebalo,M - Ocantos,M Arvier 2007} *

