{[%evp 0,39,22,23,20,18,18,18,18,14,14,14,12,14,43,45,40,40,39,31,21,33,43,13,
22,16,46,51,50,25,27,31,33,18,45,0,0,0,42,48,45,50]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Nge2 Nbd7 9. Qc2 Re8 10. O-O
h6 11. Bh4 a5 {This move was successfully employed by Chinese super-GM Ding
Liren and a few more strong players. Black makes it more difficult to start
the minority attack with b2-b4. Also, in some cases the second player could
consider the expansion with ...b7-b5-b4, although it weakens c6.} (11... Nf8
12. f3 {is covered in a separate chapter in the 1st database.}) (11... Ne4 {
was tried by many strong players, but after} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. d5
$1 {, the better piece coordination and strong d5-pawn offer White a slight
but stable positional advantage. For instance,} Nf6 (14... Nb6 15. Rfd1 {
leads to the same, as Black has to capture on d5.}) 15. Rfd1 $1 ({Less precise
is} 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. Rfd1 Ba6 $1 {Once the bishop gets to d3, it will
dominate White's rooks.}) 15... cxd5 {Black can hardly tolerate the strong
d5-passer for too long.} 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 Bg4 (17... b6 {was tested in
some correspondence games, but Black's position doesn't look attractive to the
human eye after} 18. Qa4 Be6 19. Rd4 Rad8 {Black neutralizes the strong
d4-rook, but the queen's rook will be active on the open c-file.} 20. Rc1 Rxd4
21. Nxd4 {De Blois Figueredo,A - Learte Pastor, T ICCF email 2011}) 18. Nc3
Rad8 19. Rxd8 Qxd8 20. h3 $14 {White's knight is superior to the bishop on g4
and the e4-pawn is a cause of worries. Valerga,D -Condino,G Villa Martelli 2017
}) ({The optimistic} 11... b5 {, played by GM Eljanov, seems somewhat
premature in view of} 12. Nb1 $1 {White can afford to spend a few tempi to
unblock the c-file.} Bb7 13. a4 Rc8 14. axb5 cxb5 {This position occured in
Gavrijski,D - Belchev,B ICCF email 2020 My new idea is the natural} 15. Qd1
$146 {It makes sense to keep b3 vacant for the knight.} a6 16. Nd2 Nb6 17. b3
$14 {White has a slight but long-lasting positional advantage due to his
structural superiority.}) (11... b6 12. Rfd1 Bb7 13. Rac1 Nf8 14. a3 Ne6 15.
Bf5 $14 {Walther,J - Samadara,Y ICCF email 2019}) 12. a3 $5 {I like this
natural move: White makes a vital move and again invites Black to show his
cards.} ({The most common alternative} 12. f3 b5 {might invite interesting
complications:} 13. e4 b4 14. Na4 dxe4 15. fxe4 c5 $132 {With complex,
double-edged play.}) 12... Nh5 (12... b5 {weakens c6 and doesn't seem to
provide Black with sufficient counterplay.} 13. h3 Bb7 {, as in Villarreal,B -
Mikhailov,V ICCF email 2020 can be naturally met by} ({I also examined} 13...
Ba6 $146 14. Rfc1 Nb6 15. a4 $1 {The most energetic way to exploit Black's
structural drawbacks.} b4 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Bxa6 {It turns out that exchanging
the light-squared bishops doesn't help Black.} Rxa6 18. Nb1 $14) 14. Rfc1 $5
$146 Nb6 ({After} 14... a4 {, Black secures c4 for his knight, but this
achievement doesn't fully compensate for all his issues} 15. Re1 Nb6 16. f3 Nc4
17. Bf2 $14 {The e3-e4 break will make the knight on c4 rather unstable, while
the other black pieces are ineffective.}) 15. a4 {White favourably fixes the
pawn structure on the queenside.} b4 16. Nb1 Nc4 17. Nd2 Nxd2 18. Qxd2 $14 {
Black has no compensation for his weak c6-pawn.}) (12... Nf8 {leads to one of
the tabiyas, with a2-a3 and a7-a5 included. In my opinion, this is an
unfavourable change for Black because it diminishes the effect of the ...c6-c5
break.} 13. f3 Ne6 14. a4 $1 {A decent prophylactic move. White can live with
weakening the b4-square.} b6 ({I also examined} 14... Nh5 15. Bf2 Bh4 16. g3
Be7 17. e4 $14 {Black's pieces are misplaced, so this thematic break works
perfectly.}) 15. Rad1 Bb7 16. Kh1 $14 {Carlsen,M - Anton Guijarro,D chess24.
com INT 2022}) 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Rae1 Nf8 {This position occurred in Giri,A -
Ding,L chess24.com INT 2022 In my opinion, White can exploit the vulnerability
of the dark squares on the queenside with} 15. Na4 $5 $146 Nf6 ({The attempt
to create some threats on the kingside with} 15... Qg5 {fails to} 16. Nb6 Rb8
17. Qc5 Bh3 18. Ng3 $14 {, and the a5-pawn is gone.}) ({In case of} 15... Bg4
16. Nb6 Rad8 17. Nc3 {, White's forces are mobilized to support the thematic
e3-e4.} Qg5 ({After} 17... Nd7 18. Nxd7 Bxd7 19. Na4 Nf6 20. Rc1 $14 {, the
pawns on b7 and a5 are targets for White's pieces on the queenside.}) 18. f3 {
The queen turns out to be very useful along the 2nd rank!} Bc8 19. Nxc8 Rxc8
20. Qf2 {Nothing can prevent White from occupying the centre with e3-e4.}) 16.
Nf4 Ne6 17. h3 $1 {A decent prophylactic move. White makes space for his king
and restricts Black's minor pieces.} Nxf4 {I find this move the most
challenging. After all, Black gets 2 rooks for the queen.} ({After} 17... Bd7
18. Nxe6 Bxe6 19. Nc5 Qc7 20. b4 $14 {, the minority attack is quite annoying.
Black is doomed to passive defence.}) 18. exf4 Qc7 {This is the lesser evil.} (
{The more ambitious} 18... Qxe1 19. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 20. Kh2 {backfires:} Bd7 21. Nc5
Rb8 22. g4 $16 {Black's rooks are ineffective because they lack open files.
Also, there are few targets for White's pieces and the black king is under
