{[%evp 0,33,22,19,27,18,14,14,14,15,15,15,15,13,39,42,39,31,38,16,16,16,16,14,
27,25,32,17,21,27,27,31,28,21,37,26]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5
5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Be7 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Nge2 h6 (9... Re8 10. O-O h6 11.
Bh4 Nh5) 10. Bh4 Re8 11. O-O Nh5 {The same approach as in all the systems with
Nf6-h5: By exchanging the bishops, Black partly solves his space issues and
makes it harder for White to play ... e3-e4, as e3 is under the control of
Black's heavy pieces. On the downside, the h5-knight is temporarily out of
play.} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. a3 {I like this useful waiting move: White can still
consider the standard plan with b2-b4 or the expansion in the centre with
f2-f3. At the same time, Black will have to decide where he wants to host the
queen's knight.} Nf8 ({Another sensible knight's move is} 13... Nb6 {, and
then the central strategy seems to work for White:} 14. Rae1 Bd7 (14... Nf6 15.
Nc1 Be6 16. Nb3 Ne4 17. f3 Nxc3 18. Qxc3 $14 {led to the same character of
position, where Black is doomed to passive defence. Meyner,H-Loeffelbein,K
DESC email 2013}) 15. Nc1 Rad8 16. b4 {Now Black cannot meet f2-f3 with c6-c5
anymore.} Nf6 17. Nb3 Ne4 {Natural play by both sides led to this position in
Nabaty, T - Sargissian,G Terme Catez 2021 My natural improvement over Tamir's
play is} 18. f3 $146 Nxc3 ({After} 18... Nd6 19. e4 dxe4 20. fxe4 Ndc4 21. Qf2
$36 {Black really misses his knights around the king.}) 19. Qxc3 Bc8 20. e4 $14
{White has a stable space advantage.}) (13... a5 {tranposes to Giri - Ding
Liren from the other Chapter.}) ({The ambitious} 13... Qg5 14. Kh1 Ndf6 {
left the queen on g5 awkwardly placed, and White can exploit this with} 15. Ng1
$1 Nd7 {This was Kavalerov,A - Burmakin,V St Petersburg 1994 The most
energetic was} 16. f4 $1 $146 Qd8 17. Rae1 Nhf6 18. Nf3 $14 {White will get an
optimal setup with a strong e5-knight and good attacking prospects on the
kingside.}) 14. b4 {Since most of the opponent's pieces are located on the
kingside, the traditional plan of attack against the c6-pawn is more effective.
} a6 ({After} 14... Nf6 15. b5 {, Black has nothing better than accepting the
isolated pawn:} c5 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. Qb2 Bg4 18. Rfc1 $14 {d5 will be under
permanent pressure.}) 15. Na4 {White takes advantage of the somewhat weakening
last move.} Ne6 16. Nc5 Ng5 17. a4 $14 {Black's manoeuvring play on the
kingside isn't impressive, while White's minority attack is in progress.
Feiler,J - Lang,A Baden 2018} *

