{[%evp 0,39,23,21,19,7,7,0,15,13,13,13,-3,-3,15,0,8,8,9,8,8,-1,-1,3,14,-27,17,
23,37,42,44,44,51,12,27,19,26,11,48,43,49,49]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4.
cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {This is Black's second choice by statistics. By
making this move, Black accepts the damage to his pawn structure, but he
reasonably relies on his bishop pair in the arising endgame.} 7. Qf3 {By far
the most common and most challenging for Black.} ({In contrast to 6...h6 7.Bh4
Bf5, the exchange of bishops doesn't seem to offer White anything here:} 7. Bd3
Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Na6 9. Nge2 Nc7 10. O-O Be7 11. f3 Ne6 12. Bh4 Qd7 13. Rad1 Rd8
14. Kh1 h6 15. b3 ({Premature is} 15. e4 $6 Nxe4 $1 16. Bxe7 Nxc3 $17) 15...
O-O 16. e4 Nh5 {Black had sufficient counterplay due to his control of f4 in
Grischuk,A - Andreikin,D Tbilisi 2015}) ({Also harmless seems} 7. Qb3 Qb6 8.
Bxf6 gxf6 {White still cannot avoid trading queens.} 9. Kd2 Nd7 10. Bd3 {
This was Vachier Lagrave,M - Anand,V Chess.com INT 2020 In my opinion, the
most convincing way to equality was} Bxd3 $146 11. Kxd3 f5 $1 {A standard
approach: White struggles to make progress on the kingside now.} 12. Qxb6 axb6
13. Nge2 Ke7 14. Ng3 Kf6 $11) 7... Bg6 (7... Be6 {is an interesting sideline
that was employed many times by GM Zvjaginsev. The point is that the endgame
that arises after 8.Bxf6 turns acceptable for Black as the e6-bishop isn't in
danger.} 8. Bd3 {I like this rare move that has only been played twice. White
switches to usual Carlsbad paths, since the Be6 is placed quite passively.}
Nbd7 9. h3 ({Inaccurate is} 9. Nge2 $6 h6 {, and White is forced to concede
his bishop in view of the threat ...g7-g5.}) 9... Qb6 {This was Korobov,A -
Kuzubov,Y Chess.com INT 2020.} ({After} 9... Be7 10. Nge2 O-O 11. Nf4 {, Black
suffers due to his misplaced e6-bishop.}) {White should have ignored Black's
last move with} 10. Nge2 $146 {, and then the only challenging move} Qxb2 $6 {
is refuted by} 11. Rb1 Qa3 12. Rxb7 Bb4 13. O-O Bxc3 14. Rb3 $16 {, regaining
the piece and obtaining a huge positional advantage.}) 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 ({By
leaving the queens on the board, Black takes too much risk:} 8... gxf6 $6 9. h4
h5 ({In the event of} 9... Bb4 10. h5 Be4 11. Qd1 {, the bishop on e4 is in
big danger. Play might continue:} Rg8 12. Nge2 Kf8 13. a3 $16 {White has the
better piece coordination and the safer king. Vaznonis,V - Sulskis,S Kaunas
2008}) 10. Nh3 Bd6 ({Hardly better is} 10... Bb4 11. Nf4 Nd7 12. Bd3 $36) 11.
Nf4 Nd7 12. g3 Qb6 13. O-O-O $36 {Black's king turns permanently weak.
Gonzalez,F-Compte Jornet,E Catalunya 1996}) 9. Qxf6 gxf6 10. Nf3 Nd7 {The most
sensible choice - there are no other prospects for the knight on b8.} (10... a5
11. Nh4 Bb4 {was recently employed by a few strong grandmasters. The main idea
is to lock the queenside with ...b7-b5 and ... a5-a4.} 12. Rc1 $1 {An
important preventive move.} (12. a3 {occured in most of the games, but then
after} Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 b5 $1 14. a4 bxa4 {, the strong a-passer provides Black
with decent compensation for his structural drawbacks.}) 12... Nd7 (12... a4
13. a3 Ba5 {, as in Aczel,G - Banusz,T Ajka 2021 looks artificial, and White
can develop a strong initiative with} 14. Be2 $146 Nd7 15. O-O b5 16. e4 $1 $36
) 13. a3 Bd6 ({After} 13... Bxc3+ 14. Rxc3 a4 15. Be2 Ke7 16. Kd2 $14 {Black
lacks any counterplay and White can slowly expand on the kingside or in the
centre with f2-f3 and e3-e4. Of course, Black's position is still very solid,
but it is a game for two results only.}) {This position was reached in Kuzubov,
Y - Bluebaum,M Chess.com INT 2020 In my opinion, White should have continued:}
14. f4 $146 {Black faces problems with his poor bishop.} Ke7 15. f5 Bh5 16. g3
$16 {The h5-bishop will hardly get out.}) 11. Nh4 Be7 {The most common move.
Black develops his bishop and keeps an eye on the knight on h4, having in mind
the possibility of ...f7-f5. The other options are covered in a separate
Chapter.} 12. Ne2 $1 {This move became very common after the masterpiece game
Carlsen - Kramnik. The positional threat of 13.Ng3, occupying the f5-spot,
forces Black to show his cards.} ({The common alternative is} 12. g3 {, but
then Black manages to transfer his knight to a perfect spot:} Nb6 13. O-O-O Nc8
14. Bd3 Nd6 {This position occurred in a couple of games, including Ding,L -
Kramnik,V Moscow 2014. The practical tests prove that Black's setup is
extremely solid here.}) 12... f5 {The most consistent, although locking the
g6-bishop this way isn't to everyone's taste.} ({White's strategic ideas were
fully illustrated in the following top-level game:} 12... Nb6 13. Ng3 $1 Bb4+
14. Kd1 Na4 15. Ngf5 {The b2-pawn is untouchable, so Black's counterplay is
