{[%evp 0,39,23,19,19,7,7,7,13,13,-3,-3,-3,-3,15,9,9,9,10,9,9,3,3,3,3,-12,39,41,
32,36,34,35,45,53,55,20,33,17,40,32,30,22]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4.
cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 10. Nf3 Nd7
11. Nh4 Nb6 {The knight moves towards d6 - the perfect spot for it in this
line.} (11... Bb4 12. Kd2 {This move is vital because it allows White to
connect the rooks and prepares Bd3. Also, in case of an exchange on c3, White
has the option to recapture with his king.} Nb6 13. a3 Bxc3+ ({Too passive is} 
13... Be7 {Savina,A - Efimov,I Nicolosi 2014} 14. Bd3 $146 {, and if} Nc4+ {
then} 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. g4 $1 O-O-O 17. Nf5 $14 {Black's bishop pair is fully
neutralized, so Black is left with a poor pawn structure.}) 14. Kxc3 Nc8 {
This position occurred in Van Bommel,T - Goreczny, G LSS email 2015. I suggest
the following new idea:} 15. Kd2 {White comfortably covers f2 in view of the
coming ...Nd6-e4} Nd6 16. Rc1 a5 17. b3 $1 {A decent move that allows White to
keeps everything in control: the c4-square is covered and ...a5-a4 can be met
by b3-b4 at any moment.} Ke7 18. g3 Ne4+ 19. Ke2 $14 {White can slowly make
progress on the kingside with f2-f3, Kf2, Bh3 and so on. At some point he will
choose between..e3-e4 and advancing the h and g pawns.}) (11... O-O-O {occured
in a few correspondence games, but after} 12. f4 $1 {, Black faces the same
problems as in the mainline, under even worse conditions:} h5 13. Kf2 Nb6 14.
h3 ({The immediate} 14. f5 {is equally good.}) 14... Bd6 15. f5 Bh7 16. Be2 $16
{The bishop on h7 will hardly get out. Kuster, Z - Sueess,F ICCF email 2019})
12. f4 $1 {The most common and promising move. White creates a strong threat
and poses Black some concrete problems.} f5 {Preventing f4-f5. This is a very
committal move, though, the f5-pawn is extremely weak now and the bishop on g6
is blocked.} ({In case of} 12... h5 13. Kf2 Nc8 14. f5 {, the bishop will be
completely out of play and Black doesn't seem to get any compensation.} Bh7 15.
h3 Nd6 16. g4 {Bluebaum,M - Naiditsch,A Minsk 2017}) ({Equally bad is} 12... h6
{, although it was tried in some correspondence games} 13. f5 Bh7 14. Kf2 a6
15. Bd3 $16 {Black was positionally busted. Bastos,P - Colin,S ICCF email 2016}
) 13. Bd3 Nc4 {This knight should be liquidated, as otherwise, Black can play .
..Nd6.} ({After} 13... Be7 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 15. Bxf5 Nc4 16. Nd1 $1 $16 {White is
just up a pawn.}) 14. Bxc4 dxc4 15. Kf2 Be7 {Black temporarily takes the
pressure off the weak f5-pawn.} ({After} 15... c5 16. Rhd1 Rc8 17. Rac1 $16 {
Black's lack of development starts to tell. Carlsen,M - Sharafiev,A Chess.com
INT 2017}) (15... O-O-O 16. a4 c5 {, as in Williams,S - Hawkins,J London 2015 ,
should be met by} 17. Nf3 $1 $146 cxd4 18. Nxd4 Bg7 19. Rhd1 $16 {White has a
big positional advantage due to his more active pieces and weak f5-pawn.}) 16.
Nf3 f6 {Black covers e5 and vacates f7 for his bishop.} 17. a4 {White prevents
the possible . ..b7-b5.} (17. d5 $5 {is also worth attention.}) 17... Bf7 18.
Nh4 Be6 19. Ne2 {The knight is moving towards g3.} O-O-O 20. Rhc1 $14 {The
structural superiority outweighs Black's bishop pair. Lupulescu,C - Sedlak,N
