{[%evp 0,41,19,27,27,16,13,13,21,-3,54,54,57,57,71,43,43,54,62,62,58,47,47,46,
46,44,44,42,42,13,17,5,5,3,-2,2,-6,-22,10,-32,-54,-54,-48,-35]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {The Semi-Tarrasch became very popular in the last
decades mainly due to the efforts of GM Vladimir Kramnik, who successfully
played it on the highest level.} 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. Rb1 {This is the
second choice by statistics. I like it because it allows White to avoid the
immediate exchange of dark-squared bishop. Also, the rook is quite active and
makes it harder for the opponent to develop his light-squared bishop.} ({
The big theoretical line starts with} 7. Nf3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+) 7... cxd4 {
By releasing the tension in the centre, Black intends to exploit the
vulnerability of White's king along the a5-e1 diagonal.} ({The provocative} 
7... Nc6 $6 {is met by} 8. d5 exd5 9. exd5 Qe7+ ({Even worse is} 9... Na5 $2
10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Qe2+ Qe7 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 13. Be3 $18 {, with a decisive
advantage - Black's king is stuck in the centre, and the a5-knight is out of
play.}) 10. Be3 Ne5 11. Nf3 a6 12. Rb2 $16 {White has both superior
development and a strong passer. Lang,F - Beckett,P ICCF email 2018}) ({
The greedy} 7... Qa5 $6 8. Bd2 Qxa2 9. Nf3 {leaves Black too undeveloped. For
instance,} Bd6 10. Bd3 c4 11. Ra1 Qb3 12. Bc2 Qb6 13. e5 $16 {White will
develop a stunning attack with 14.Ng5, while Black's extra pawn doesn't really
make a difference. Degraeve,J - Leroy,D Drancy 2016}) 8. cxd4 Nc6 9. Nf3 ({
Another common try is} 9. Bb5 a6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Nf3 c5 12. O-O Be7 {
This interesting position was tested a few times on high level, and it looks
like Black should be able to slowly solve his development issues.}) 9... Bb4+ {
The most consistent. Black suffers from a lack of space, so any exchange
should favour him.} ({Too passive is} 9... Be7 10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O b6 12. Bb2 {
All White's minor pieces are placed perfectly now.} Bb7 13. Qe2 {Vacating d1
for the rook.} Rc8 14. Rfd1 Na5 15. Bb5 $14 {Black was doomed to passive
defence because of White's strong pawn centre and his poor a5-knight. Vitiugov,
N - Adly,A Tsaghkadzor 2015}) ({Definitely not to be recommended is} 9... Qa5+
$2 10. Bd2 Qxa2 11. Bc3 Qa3 {The queen escapes, but it takes too much time.}
12. Rb3 Qe7 13. Be2 {After 14.d5, White will obtain a nearly decisive attack.})
10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 O-O ({Premature is} 11... Qa5 $6 12. Bb5 Bd7 13. d5
Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 $16 {Cramling,P - Vaisser,A Cap d'Agde 1996}) 12. Bb5 Ne7 {
The most common choice. Black reasonably assumes, that more defenders are
needed on the kingside in the long run.} ({There are also a few alternatives
at Black's disposal:} 12... Bd7 13. O-O Rc8 {Black is trying to create some
counterplay along the c-file, but it is too slow.} ({In case of} 13... a6 14.
Bd3 b5 {, White should act aggressively:} 15. d5 $1 exd5 16. exd5 Ne7 17. d6
$16 {The d-passer was too strong in Coto Mederos,M - Obolenskikh,D Chess.com
INT 2022}) 14. d5 exd5 15. exd5 Ne7 {This position occurred in Shamkovich,
L-Boleslavsky,I Riga 1961 In my opinion, White shouldn't deviate from the most
tempting} 16. d6 $1 $146 Ng6 17. h3 {White has time to make space for his king.
} ({The aggressive} 17. h4 $5 {also comes into consideration.}) 17... Rc5 18.
Bxd7 Qxd7 19. Rfe1 Rd8 20. Rb3 $36 {The d6-pawn is untouchable in view of Re8+,
and that's why Black's pieces are practically paralyzed.}) (12... Qd6 13. O-O
b6 {took place in Shevchenko,K - Druska,J Skopje 2019 In my opinion, White can
take advantage of his superior piece coordination with} (13... Rd8 14. Rfd1 Bd7
{, as in Kiriakov,P-Kron,V Orel 1992 , can be well met by} 15. e5 $146 Qc7 16.
Qf4 h6 17. Qe4 $14 {, with decent attacking prospects.}) 14. e5 $146 Qd5 15.
Bd3 $1 {The Bd3 has an important role in the upcoming attack.} h6 {A decent
prophylactic move, but Black spends a significant tempo.} ({After} 15... Bb7
16. Rb5 Qd7 17. d5 exd5 18. Rxd5 $36 {, it is very hard to withstand the
activity of White's pieces.}) 16. Rfe1 Qd7 (16... Bb7 17. Rb5 Qd7 18. d5 $36)
17. Re4 Ne7 18. Rg4 {White's attacking potential looks threatening when most
of his pieces are involved.}) (12... Na5 {Similar to 12...Ne7, Black intends
to develop his light-squared bishop, but the a5-knight is temporarily out of
play.} 13. O-O b6 14. d5 {I see no reason to reject this key break.} exd5 15.
exd5 Qd6 {This attempt to set up a blockade took place in Ramirez Alvarez,A -
Cernousek,L Chess. com INT 2020. White should have secured his passer with} ({
After} 15... Bb7 16. d6 Bxf3 17. gxf3 $36 {, the strong d6-passer paralyzes
Black's pieces, while White's king is still safe.}) 16. Rb4 $1 $146 Rd8 17. Rd4
{, and then after} Bd7 18. Bc6 Rac8 19. Rd1 $14 {, Black struggles to release
the pressure.}) 13. O-O b6 ({The more active} 13... a6 14. Bd3 b5 15. Rfc1 Bb7
{was seen in Novik,M - Davtyan,D Chess.com INT 2021 White could have exploited
the drawbacks of the weakening b7-b5 with} 16. a4 $1 f5 17. Re1 fxe4 18. Bxe4
$14 {Black has no sufficient compensation for his inferior pawn structure.})
14. h4 $1 {The advance of the h-pawn restricts the mobility of the knight on
e7 and puts Black's kingside under pressure.} Bb7 15. Rfe1 Rc8 {There is
hardly a more useful move at Black's disposal.} ({Less accurate is} 15... Qd6
16. d5 $1 exd5 17. e5 Qg6 18. Bd3 {, with a powerful initiative.}) 16. h5 h6 {
Natural play by both sides led to this position in So,W - Duda,J chess24.com
INT 2021. Here I prefer} 17. Rbd1 $146 {White shows his intention to push
forward in the centre.} Qd6 ({After} 17... Qc7 18. d5 exd5 19. e5 Qc3 20. Qf4
$40 {, Black fails to benefit from having the active queen on c3 and White's
attack develops fast.}) 18. d5 $1 {This thematic break seems promising.} Rc5 $1
{This cold-blooded response is the most challenging for White.} ({Much worse is
} 18... exd5 $2 19. e5 Qe6 20. Qf4 $16 {White's initiative develops itself,
while Black's extra pawn has no value.}) 19. Bd3 {The bishop did its job, so
now it should join the attack.} exd5 20. e5 Qd7 21. Nd4 $44 {White has
promising play for the pawn due to his better piece coordination and the
potential threat of e5-e6.} *

